We put the door back on and when a statue of Mary was placed beside it for comparison, we couldn't unsee it!  We took pictures and posted them on our Facebook page and the following day the post went viral!  For more images and information see: https://t.co/VilB1HR612

We didn't originally notice anything unusual about the cabinet and even had the door removed to make use of the internal shelves to display vinyl records. It wasn't until 10 months later when a customer spotted the door at the back of the shop and brought it to our attention.

We know little enough as to the origins of the display cabinet other than that it is mahogany/walnut, Edwardian c.1910 - 1915, stamped Greenlands Ltd, of Hereford England. It came from a residence in Northern Ireland before being purchased by a Tralee man.

Another interesting fact about the cabinet is that if the door is removed and turned upside down, the image can be interpreted in the same way, but the resemblance becomes stronger. This phenomenon is known as Pareidolia, seeing recognizable objects or faces in inanimate objects.
